To control the inverter, the grid voltages are measured and used to determine the grid angle Î¸ by means of phase lock loop (PLL). (Isen et al. 2016) explain the PLL method in detail. The grid angle is then used in Parkâs transformation to transform the grid voltages (Vga, Vgb and Vgc) from a-b-c reference frame to d-q frame which simplifies the control, and the result is Vgd and Vgq (the d-q components of the grid voltages). Following the same transformation method, Vid and Viq (the d-q inverter components) are generated from the output voltages of the inverter. Parkâs transformation is given as (Isen et al. 2016):12VdVq=23cosÎ¸cosÎ¸-2Ï3cosÎ¸-4Ï3-sinÎ¸-sinÎ¸-2Ï3-sinÎ¸-4Ï3VaVbVc\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
